✨Blanksgiving 2022✨
 
It’s taken me over a week to post about this night bc it’s hard to put into words what it means to me. 
 
Blanksgiving started organically a couple years ago. The salon had gone through a hard transition people wise a few months earlier and we hadn’t really gotten together since. 
 
The Tuesday before Thanksgiving of 2019 we all ended up at one of the local bars. We got drinks an apps and loved on each other and it was much much needed. 
 
Since then it’s become a tradition. The Tuesday before Thanksgiving, anyone who can, gathers after a crazy day for a drink and some fun outside of work.
 
This year has been the most special because it wasn’t just @blankcanvasnh that gathered… it was also our humans from the @blankcanvasstudiosnh  @rossisbarbershopnh, and our friends from @arborandroot! Additionally, we had significant others who work at other salons/shops come! 
 
This night was was such a testament to how beautiful the community were building is. Blanksgiving has grown so much that next year we will be shutting down the salon at a certain time and having an open house for all our local industry friends! 
 
It’s nights like this that show me we ARE making a difference. And it’s beautiful. 
 
*we didn’t get everyone who came through on one photo but there were 40-50 and that melts my heart 🥰

There’s one hair out of place and it irritates me. But this color is 🤌🏼 so here we are!

✨2022✨
 
This year i wasn’t focused on the hair i did or the money we brought in. I was focused on growing my community, the connections I made, and the humans i loved and loved me back.

I said goodbye to 6 humans that helped set the tone at Blank Canvas for the last 4 years. Luckily we are all still close, and right through the woods!

@jojolumpy and I sold our condo, moved into an upscale apartment and are ending the year in a new place on water 🥰

*Monday Motivation*
 
This sound really resonated with me this morning. 
 
Don’t get me wrong, having plans are important… but nothing goes to plan. And every time I’ve said, “i will NEVER do this again” (ex: building a salon), a few years down the line I find myself hungry for a challenge. 
 
Ive built 3 salons in 8 years and in the middle of each process i usually have a melt down of “what am i doing?!?”. By the end, im so happy to have made it through that i just go about my business.

We have never had a grand opening for any place I’ve built. We’ve never celebrated even with a cheers… because im constantly thinking “what could i do to make it better?” 
 
Maybe that’s part of it. Maybe I need therapy. Idk lol but one thing I know is I might never feel done, so I need to stop and appreciate what I’ve built.
 
Blank Canvas (started off as Lush ) and has morphed into one of the largest salons in New England. We have incredible stylist retention. We have a multi year waiting list for every position from Apprentice-Studio Renter. We have housed multiple future salon owners. We’ve helped three humans get their licenses through apprenticeships. We’ve given a safe space for over 50 stylists to grow individually since 2017. 
 
So today I’m proud not just because we’ve built 3 beautiful spaces, but because we’ve created 3 safe spaces for stylists to absolutely flourish. 🥰 
 
 
And i hope to keep going 😁🫶🏼
 
What are you proud of today?

✨Danger Jones✨
This will be a long ass post but first… this first photo is by @stevieangeliquey!
 
I’ve been in the industry for over 16 years. I’ve been in the instagram game since 2015. I’ve seen a lot, and experienced a lot and I’m super grateful.
 
One thing i never wanted to be was an educator. Not only did i not have the confidence, i never loved any product enough to vouch for them… until in 2016 i was given the opportunity to be involved with a new color line, Pulp Riot. To make a long story short, I got to know the Thurston’s personally and I was sold. Not only was the product amazing, these are genuine people. 
 
They were the first people in the industry to believe i had what it takes to do more than i was doing. I got to be on every national main stage, traveled to states and cities i would have never seen to educate. I got to go to Italy to help formulate a permanent color line! And they *always* wanted to do the right thing by their people and industry. (This is my personal experience)
 
Since starting my Instagram, I’ve supported 3 companies: Pulp Riot, Olaplex & Framar. I still rep Olaplex and Framar (also started supporting them in 2016). I stayed with Pulp until this past July when I resigned as an educator, bc it didn’t feel right for me anymore with all the changes.
 
I’m as genuine as they come. I don’t deal with shit people. I stick hard to my morals, and integrity & loyalty are very important to me. When i get behind something, you know it’s more than just a good product. It’s good people. 
 
Im excited I have been given the opportunity to work with @dangerjonescreative, and the Thurston’s again (not to mention a bunch of my friends)!
 
Im excited for March when I’ll get to go out to LA with friends to play with the color and to reconnect. It’s been a minute.
 
My point of this post, is to say i feel rejuvenated. I feel inspired and creative! Im working with people i admire and respect. Not many people get a round one.. but to get a round two is beyond wild to me.
 
I am forever grateful for every opportunity i receive, especially when i believe in it in my soul. 🫶🏼
 
Bring on March! 🙌🏼

🌿Moss Wall Update🌿
 
Ok first, this sound is me 100%!! 😂
 
Life for in the way for a little while but I’ve finally been able to put in some work on this!
 
I think I’m about 8 hours in and juuuuust about half way! 
 
If you’re just joining, I’m making a decorative #mosswall inside of @blankcanvasstudiosnh ! I@ using preserved moss (real moss that is no longer living but looks, smells and feels like living moss. This is not fake moss!) I’m also using a hot glue gun to attach it! @he_runs_withclippers installed large pieces of plywood so years down the road if we don’t want it, we can just take off the plywood instead of damaging the whole wall.
 
Things I’ve learned:
🌱Your hands are going to be VERY green.
🌱Don’t use too hot of a glue or it will dry it out 
🌱The larger glue guns/sticks seem to dry out the moss less
🌱buying in bulk off Amazon saves money, but in my opinion you get larger (easier to attach) sizes in the bags at the craft store
🌱Supermoss brand is what i use
 
 
Have any questions?! Feel free to ask!

Danger Jones: Unplugged🫶🏼
 
I’ve had the pleasure of knowing @davidthurstonofficial and @alexisbutterflyloft since 2016. Since then, they have changed my life. They have shown me parts of the industry i would never have been able to experience. And they’ve *always* shown me love, respect and loyalty since day one.

I’ve also known and had the pleasure of spending time and educating with @rubydevine @dougtheo @maryh.ott, @mermeghair and @marimia for many, many years. As Ruby says, “my biggest flex in the industry is who my friends are”. It’s so true. The depth of each relationship is not determined by time spent, but by the experiences that have bonded us ❤️ 

Yesterday, i had the absolute honor of having all of them in my very special second home, @blankcanvasnh. I’ve spent 6 years pouring my heart and soul into Blank Canvas and to have mentors and humans i admire and look up to educating in there is a dream come true.l!

But the number one thing that makes Blank Canvas what it is, is my team. 40+ humans between the salon and studios who have a common goal, and that’s to elevate the industry through community. Every human we have is a caring, contributing part of our ecosystem and they are what I’m most proud of. To show off Blank Canvas is to show off the humans who make it the magical place it is. 

Last but not least… my business partners @dialynros and @jojolumpy. Without them, there would be no salon. I may be good at connecting with people, but i sure do suck at hard decisions and finances 😅😂
 
Thank you to everyone who came out last night. We hosted our second largest class with over 65 people in the building! Blank Canvas was always meant to be a community space and when it’s filled with those in our community is when it’s at its best. 

@dangerjonescreative isn’t your typical brand. The humans behind it aren’t creating for commerce, they’re creating for art and fulfillment.. and that’s what makes it what it is. 
 
✨It was always about the people✨

*5 tips i wish i knew when i was starting out with vibrants*
 
1: leave a little yellow in the bleach out. 
I used to try to lift my vibrant clients to a level 17 lol... Leaving them at a 9 will give you better hold to the colors and also leave the hair stronger for removal. If you need to tone for ashy colors, do it at a 9.

2: Saturation. Saturation. Saturation.
Speeding through the application helps no one. Take each section and really check to make sure you’ve thoroughly saturated. I like to go back through and open up my sections to make sure I’ve gotten every last bit of blonde fully saturated.
 
3: Condition after the bleach out.
I know, i know. Every semi company will tell you not to condition after bleaching bc it will prevent the color from being able to stain as well. I’m here to tell you for the last 7 years, I’ve done a light condition with a good rinse after every bleach out. It helps porosity, makes the deranging and blow dry more comfortable for the client, and I’ve never ever had any saturation issues. Ever.

4: Root and color in quadrants rather than rooting the whole head at once. 
I used to root the whole head at once and then go back and color the midshaft and ends. I started to find that by the time i was halfway through, the color had encapsulated and i struggled with blending the colors together. If you go quadrant by quadrant (or smaller sections) you’ll get a better blend. 
 
5: Go a bit deeper than your inspo.
Often times i get inspo pics of lighter colors, and i looooove playing with pastels… but paying clients need longevity in their color to feel like there is value. If i get an inspo pic of pastels, i always chat with my client about going a bit deeper so they have more longevity once they leave.

I hope some of these helped! Which was your favorite tip? Do you already do this? Lmk ⬇️

Matrix Bleach Finder! (This is NOT a sponsored post). What a game changer! This shampoo is part of their “unbreak my blonde” line and works by turning pink if there is still lightener in the hair. It is also a ph balancer, and helps revitalize hair with citric acid! 
 
You can see in the first part of the reel the pink suds. The second part of the reel it comes out of the bottle a yellow color. If there is no bleach, it stays yellow. If there is bleach, pink!
 
One of the hardest things is getting all the bleach out of the hair. Those tiny particles don’t come out with one wash. Often times, you need to wash two or three times to fully get it out. 
 
How do you know if you got all the lightener out without this product? You will feel it when drying the hair and your vibrants will definitely show it. If you’ve ever had spotty results even though you KNOW you saturated, or if the color looks different when it hits the hair or scalp than what came out of the tube. Oxidation is one of the main concerns after bleaching. When residual lightener in your hair remains undetected, it can lead to oxidation which can be detrimental to vibrancy, longevity, and overall hair health.
 
Again, this is not a sponsored post..this is actually the only matrix product i use.. but wow has it made a difference!

Want to have a vibrant clientele but are having a tough time getting them in your chair? Here are three tips I’ve used to grow from all root retouches and foils, to multiple vibrants and week!
 
⭐️ Do models. For free or almost free. Yes. I said it. Free or almost free. I know it can be hard to put out money for product, plus time and not get paid. But i found the trade off to be well worth it. Getting that person in your chair and having freedom to put your art on a walking billboard is hands down better than boosting a post. The money you “lose” on product and time for that model will pay off when people ask who and where they got their hair done.
 
⭐️Go to an art school. Or a Starbucks. Or anywhere you see people able to express themselves and give them your social info and have them check you out. Offer a discount to those people to get them in. Do you know how many people Starbucks workers see in a day? Again.. walking advertisement.
 
⭐️this will seem like a no brainer but you have no idea how many people don’t utilize social media properly. I don’t even anymore if we’re being honest. Post post post post post. Every day. Use hashtags (so many “coaches” telling you they don’t matter but they still do 😉). DM fellow artists. Tattoo artists, nail techs, massage therapists. Offer a referral program with fellow industry pros. Networking is so helpful and social media has made it that much easier to do!
 
I hope some of these tips help. They helped me grow so much when i was trying to start up a vibrant clientele and they still work for my stylists today who want to specialize in vibrants.

I’ve been specializing in vibrants for a little over 8 years. I’ve used most color lines, and tried just about every tip and trick. I’ve also found a few of my own! 
 
✨Conditioning after bleaching. This used to be a no no, and is still taught not to. While using a heavy conditioner or even a moisturizing one can create a barrier, not all conditioners are made the same. I usually use a volumizing or light daily conditioner. This way, I’m not ripping through the hair at its most fragile state, and it can help with porosity. I’ve never, ever found it to be harmful to the color outcome.
 
✨Shampoo out your vibrants. I learned this from @mermeghair . Now, i tend to use the most gentle shampoo, and i only scrub lightly on the scalp for less than a minute. Why? Well it’s been found to help reduce bleeding onto the skin, pillows, towels, etc… and, no effect on longevity. 
 
✨I don’t add a bond builder. For lightening? Sure, go for it (although i really don’t). I’m talking about IN your vibrants. No shade to anyone that does, I’ve just found it to not be necessary. When using a bond builder, you’re looking to reduce breakage from the lightening process. The hair during the lightening process is in a fragile state, and the bond builder is directly interacting with the makeup of the hair. When put into a semi, a type of color that has things in it to help create a barrier for a hair (semi color sits on the hair and can stain it), it’s most likely not able to do enough to make it worth wasting your money.

Advanced Tips from a Vivid Specialist 👇🏼 
 
✨Permanent Red and Semi Red can touch 😧. Yup. The big rule is you can’t have a permanent (and usually a demi permanent) touch because the ammonia/peroxide will “eat” the semi and you’ll have a weird line of demarcation. 100% true….. except for reds. I personally will apply my red root color, then put the semi on the ends with them slightly melting into each other (don’t over work it). I mix a tiny bit extra so when i rinse, i can do a quick mask with it all over in the sink! This is such a time saver for me with reds rather than waiting for it to process and then applying the semi.
 
✨This might be the most controversial one… If I see a spot I missed or didn’t saturate enough when I’m styling, I apply the vibrant over that spot and continue my blow dry. Yuuuup i blow dry it in. A semi color is basically a conditioner with pigment in it. It’s not a processing color (no ammonia/peroxide). So if there’s a little spot (less than the size of a quarter), I’ll grab a tiny bit of the semi, put it on and dry it in. It may look a touch greasy, but it covers and doesn’t damage the hair. FYI… i probably wouldn’t use a curling iron or flat iron over that spot. Extra product in the hair on a very high heat can be unpredictable. I just blow dry and it’s like blow drying over a leave in conditioner. 
 
✨I don’t do a full bleach out every time. When i have a vivid client, i plan two appointments with them. The first (when we do the full bleach out), we not only plan placement and color palette, we also plan what a refresh would look like in 6-8 weeks. This way, i allow more time in my schedule for others, it frees up their budget a little, and it helps the integrity of the hair. When they come in for the refresh, we apply the semi colors to the root, and do panels of the other main colors throughout the hairs leaving some of the fade for “highlights”.

Porosity Issues!
 
But how did we get here?
 
Here are contributing factors to porosity issues:
✨Overlapping when lightening the roots
✨Over processing 
✨Products used at home
✨Temperature of hot tools
✨Washing too much 
✨And the absolute biggest one… Vivid Removal. No matter what, vivid removal is hard on the hair. For the most part, you’re lightening over previously lightened hair.. and all the products in the world can’t make that predictable. 
 
If you’re seeing this often when your vibrant clients return, here’s some things that will help:
✨Don’t remove every time. Do a refresh of just semis in between lightening appointments.
✨Do protein treatments at the sink when they are in (I love Redken CAT but i DO NOT retail it’s too strong). I said PROTEIN, not BOND BUILDER. Both great, but different. Protein and moisture together help porosity. 
✨Have your client do a deep, moisturizing conditioner once a week at home. 
✨Try using a less harsh way of removal like @malibucpro ddl & water.
 
And one final thing.. having this happen doesn’t make you a bad colorist. There are so many reasons this can happen, it’s how we repair it moving forward once we see it so it doesn’t lead to worse issues.
 
It happens to more people than you know!

I’ve spent a lot of time studying color. I play games on my phone that helps identify hues. Color theory isn’t just what cancels out or inhances what. It’s also understanding how light reacts, depth of pigments, undertones, etc. i could go on and on but let’s just focus on why we should mix dark into light.
 
Just like with natural color, an even amount of light and dark color will always fall on the darker side. Need to mix to get a 6n using 5n & 7n? Equal parts will put it at a 5.5 because of how much pigment is in a 5, vs a 7 (i would do 2/3 7 and 1/3 5 in case you were wondering.)
 
Well the same goes for semi (vivid) color. If i take a dark color and slowly add light to it, im going to use a LOT of light to get it where I need it because of how deep the color is. 
 
Now, if i put my light in and slowly add dark, im going to use less color because its going to darken much quicker because im seeing in real time how much the dark can take over the light. 
 
The same goes for mixing on the hair as well! If im color melting, im putting my lighter color on first, and blending the dark into it.

Ok ok… let’s be real. There’s *nothing* lazy about any platinum card…. BUT… it doesn’t always have to be as labor intensive. Here are some tips and tricks i like to use to reduce my application time!

 
✨Put multiple sections in each foil. 
Ok, this i will do on anyone who is a level 6 and above, has done to medium texture hair, is getting a vibrant overlay. I still fully saturated, in just will do three sections in between each foil. Helps with timing, doesn’t compromise lift (as long as you’re saturating properly).
✨I don’t fold every foil. 
I don’t see the necessity. Leaving my foils flat has always worked just fine for incubation and increases my speed.
✨Applying the root while the foils are still in. 
Using the above techniques, i find that I’m quick enough to be able to apply the root at the same time, thus not having to take time to rinse each section.
✨Use a higher developer in the back and a low developer in the front.
This is the complete opposite of what i do for highlights. When i foil, i start in the back with a lower developer and move to a higher one as I get to the end. For this style platinum card, im moving quick enough that by the time i get to the front, the back still has a bit to go. I’m not trying to weave the perfect sections and I’m not worrying about placement. The hair is also much stronger where it doesn’t see the sun, elements or get the brunt of the styling. The hair is more fragile in the front which is why i do a lower developer.
 
✨Don’t use this technique on level 5 & below.
Putting multiple sections in a foil will slow down the process just a bit. Doing this on dark levels you want to reach a 10 won’t produce ideal results.

Putting a Demi gloss over for “shine” or to “seal it in”.
 
What it won’t do:
 
✨Give more shine. 
Depending on the brand of vivid color, it will be shiny enough without adding to it. If it’s not, change up your vibrant line.
 
✨Sealing the color in.
Sealing in vivids isn’t a thing. Vivids are a stain. There is no sealing it in. If you want it to last longer, make sure you stain the hair deep enough 😉 
 
What it will do:
 
✨Pull the semi color out. 
Anything that has a process to it will eat away at a semi. Some people even use a semi color to PULL OUT pastels. Because you have a chemical reaction, it’s going to hurt the vibrancy and longevity. It’s just science. 🤷🏻‍♀️
 
✨Put added stress on the hair.
Yes, Demi’s are gentle. But it’s STILL an added process.  With a chemical reaction. If it can pull a stain out of the hair, it most definitely can add stress to already processed hair. Not like a permanent or bleach, but why even do it if there’s no added benefits? 
 
✨Waste your time and money
You will spend time and money fixing putting a Demi over a semi. My advice is to use a heavy conditioner and shine products when styling if you’re looking for a more glass like finish. @colorwowhair Dream Coat is one of the best IMO!
